<subSubSection id="C37A651C6D6B96135FAFF91882F4F8F3" pageId="1" pageNumber="302" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BDF36976D6B96135FAFF91882F4F8F3" blockId="1.[151,1436,1676,2025]" pageId="1" pageNumber="302">
<emphasis id="B914EA856D6B96135FAFF9188065F92B" bold="true" box="[199,321,1748,1773]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="302" reason="1">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="4C604D146D6B96135DDCF9198219F92A" authorityName="Andersen" authorityYear="1989" box="[692,829,1748,1772]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Baptista" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="302" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="femoralis">
<emphasis id="B914EA856D6B96135DDCF9198219F92A" box="[692,829,1748,1772]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="302">B. femoralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; however, abdominal ventrite VI and VII both possess a longitudinal median keel (
<figureCitation id="135B2A126D6B96135EB4F93B830FF8D6" box="[476,555,1783,1808]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–13" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1875,1898]" captionTargetBox="[189,1397,193,1854]" captionTargetId="figure-58@6.[189,1397,193,1854]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 10–13. Abdominal sternites of Baptista spp. (males). 10. B. digitata; 11. B. hoedli; 12. B. curvicornis sp. n.; 13. B. obtusa sp. n.. Scale 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4918943" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4918943/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="302">Fig 10</figureCitation>
), and the structure of abdominal ventrite VIII (
<figureCitation id="135B2A126D6B96135B39F93B85BAF8D6" box="[1105,1182,1783,1808]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–25" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1527,1550]" captionTargetBox="[201,1344,221,1481]" captionTargetId="figure-238@8.[166,1420,193,1506]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 21–25. Photographs of abdominal segment VIII of Baptista spp. (males); 21–24 ventral view, 25 lateral view. 21. B. digitata; 22. B. hoedli; 23. B. obtusa sp. n.; 24–25. B. curvicornis sp. n.; Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4918947" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4918947/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="302">Fig 21</figureCitation>
) readily separates the males of the two species (for 
<taxonomicName id="4C604D146D6B96135E88F8D1834EF8F2" authorityName="Andersen" authorityYear="1989" box="[480,618,1820,1844]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Baptista" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="302" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="femoralis">
<emphasis id="B914EA856D6B96135E88F8D1834EF8F2" box="[480,618,1820,1844]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="302">B. femoralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, see 
<figureCitation id="135B2A126D6B96135DCAF8D083D5F8F3" box="[674,753,1820,1845]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–17" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1944,1967]" captionTargetBox="[282,1272,219,1888]" captionTargetId="figure-87@7.[282,1304,193,1904]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 14–17. Fore legs of Baptista spp. (males). 14. B. digitata; 15. B. hoedli; 16. B. curvicornis sp. n.; 17. B. obtusa sp. n.. Scale 0.2 mm. FIGURES 18–20. Details of fore tibial venter of Baptista spp. (males). 18. B. hoedli; 19. B. curvicornis sp. n.; 20. B. obtusa sp. n.. Scale 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4918945" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4918945/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="302">
Fig. 
<quantity id="4C989B726D6B96135DBDF8D083D5F8F3" box="[725,753,1820,1845]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.064" pageId="1" pageNumber="302" unit="in" value="16.0">16</quantity>
</figureCitation>
in 
<bibRefCitation id="EFF14B666D6B96135C7DF8D082E7F8F3" author="Andersen, N. M." box="[789,963,1820,1845]" pageId="1" pageNumber="302" pagination="363 - 380" refId="ref7313" refString="Andersen, N. M. (1989) The Old World Microveliinae (Hemiptera: Veliidae). II. Three new species of Baptista Distant and a new genus from the Oriental region. Entomologica Scandinavica, 19, 363 - 380. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1163 / 187631289 x 00258" type="journal article" year="1989">Andersen 1989</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
