<subSubSection id="C37A651C6D6B96105FAFF8F38255FB2E" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="303" pageId="1" pageNumber="302" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BDF36976D6B96105FAFF8F3804EFC63" blockId="1.[151,1436,1676,2025]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1437,151,1544]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="303" pageId="1" pageNumber="302">
<emphasis id="B914EA856D6B96135FAFF8F3830FF89E" bold="true" box="[199,555,1855,1880]" pageId="1" pageNumber="302">
<emphasis id="B914EA856D6B96135FAFF8F38050F89E" box="[199,372,1855,1880]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="302" reason="1">Redescription.</emphasis>
Apterous male
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="135B2A126D6B96135D51F8F38351F89E" box="[569,629,1855,1880]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1969,1992]" captionTargetBox="[175,1411,193,1954]" captionTargetId="figure-60@3.[175,1411,193,1954]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Habitus of Baptista spp.. 1. B. digitata, male; 2. B. digitata, female; 3. B. hoedli, male; 4. B. hoedli, female; 5. B. hoedli, apterous male. Scale 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4918939" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4918939/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="302">Fig 1</figureCitation>
). Colour: ground colour dull brown, head brown, clypeus, pseudocellar spots and median line of head black, rostrum yellowish with black apex, buccula yellowish brown; antennal segments I–II dark yellow, III–IV brown; pronotum brown, with dense, black spots on posterior part, behind head, anterior margin with narrow yellowish band; legs mainly brown, basal part of femur yellowish, with apices of femora, tibiae and tarsi infuscated; abdomen dorsally and laterally dull brown, ventrally mainly yellow, laterosternite and mediotergite VII yellowish, intersegmental limits of abdomen black, hind margin of mediotergite I with some silvery pubescence; abdominal segment VIII, pygophore and proctiger yellowish, each weakly infuscated apically. Structural characteristics: body length 2.94–2.98, medium-sized for genus, elongate, bearing short, grayish, appressed pubescence, dorsum covered by relatively long, suberect, brown or silver hairs. Head about 1.36 times as wide as long, posteriorly inserted into medially concave anterior margin of pronotum; labrum angulate; buccula clearly visible; antennae long and slender, about 0.67 times as long as body, lengths of antennal segments I–IV: 0.50, 0.30, 0.58, 0.60; pronotum width: 0.88–0.91, length: 0.53–0.56, about 1.64 times as wide as long, anterior pronotal margin deeply emarginated, pronotal collar angularly widened behind eyes but ventrally narrowed, hind pronotal margin broadly rounded, posterior portion of pronotal lobe with scattered dark punctures; metanotum completely hidden beneath pronotal lobe except laterally. Legs with mainly decumbent, short setae except femur ventrally with relatively long, erect setae; fore femur modified, strongly bent on apical third, ventral margin with large, pilose preapical tumescence (
<figureCitation id="135B2A126D6896105DD4FDE8822EFDFB" box="[700,778,548,573]" captionStart="FIGURES 14–17" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1944,1967]" captionTargetBox="[282,1272,219,1888]" captionTargetId="figure-87@7.[282,1304,193,1904]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 14–17. Fore legs of Baptista spp. (males). 14. B. digitata; 15. B. hoedli; 16. B. curvicornis sp. n.; 17. B. obtusa sp. n.. Scale 0.2 mm. FIGURES 18–20. Details of fore tibial venter of Baptista spp. (males). 18. B. hoedli; 19. B. curvicornis sp. n.; 20. B. obtusa sp. n.. Scale 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4918945" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4918945/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">Fig 14</figureCitation>
); fore tibia slightly curved and thickened distally, without row of spines or protuberance ventrally, grasping comb short, only about 0.21 times tibia length; lengths of leg segments (femur, tibia, and tarsi): fore leg: 0.95, 0.80 and 0.33, middle leg: 1.00, 0.95 and 0.40 (0.16+0.24), hind leg: 1.12, 1.20 and 0.47 (0.24+0.23); mediotergites not flat, more or less depressed; connexivum approximately rectangular, distinctly raised; abdominal segments VI and VII modified both pleurally and ventrally, segment VI produced pleurally on each side into a pilose, posteriorly-directed, fingerlike projection, segment VII likewise produced pleurally on each side into a short, rounded, pilose projection (
<figureCitation id="135B2A126D6896105CD6FD30852FFCD3" box="[958,1035,764,789]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–13" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1875,1898]" captionTargetBox="[189,1397,193,1854]" captionTargetId="figure-58@6.[189,1397,193,1854]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 10–13. Abdominal sternites of Baptista spp. (males). 10. B. digitata; 11. B. hoedli; 12. B. curvicornis sp. n.; 13. B. obtusa sp. n.. Scale 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4918943" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4918943/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">Fig 10</figureCitation>
); ventrite VI and VII both possess a longitudinal median keel, laterally with a moderate depression (
<figureCitation id="135B2A126D6896105C0BFCD38294FCFE" box="[867,944,799,824]" captionStart="FIGURES 10–13" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1875,1898]" captionTargetBox="[189,1397,193,1854]" captionTargetId="figure-58@6.[189,1397,193,1854]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 10–13. Abdominal sternites of Baptista spp. (males). 10. B. digitata; 11. B. hoedli; 12. B. curvicornis sp. n.; 13. B. obtusa sp. n.. Scale 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4918943" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4918943/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">Fig 10</figureCitation>
), segment VIII (
<figureCitation id="135B2A126D6896105B00FCD38597FCFE" box="[1128,1203,799,824]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–25" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1527,1550]" captionTargetBox="[201,1344,221,1481]" captionTargetId="figure-238@8.[166,1420,193,1506]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 21–25. Photographs of abdominal segment VIII of Baptista spp. (males); 21–24 ventral view, 25 lateral view. 21. B. digitata; 22. B. hoedli; 23. B. obtusa sp. n.; 24–25. B. curvicornis sp. n.; Scale 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4918947" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4918947/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">Fig 21</figureCitation>
) about 1.43 times as long as wide, protruding behind segment VII, distinctly swollen ventrally. Genital segments: pygophore subovate; proctiger (Fig 26) narrow, with apex acute; paramere symmetrical, falciform, strongly curved, with slightly sharp apex (Figs 27, 28).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BDF36976D6896105FAFFC6382DBFB05" blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1544]" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">
<emphasis id="B914EA856D6896105FAFFC6380CFFC0E" box="[199,491,943,968]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="303" reason="1">
<emphasis id="B914EA856D6896105FAFFC6380A8FC0E" bold="true" box="[199,396,943,968]" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">Apterous female</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="135B2A126D6896105EF5FC6380F9FC0E" box="[413,477,943,968]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–5" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1969,1992]" captionTargetBox="[175,1411,193,1954]" captionTargetId="figure-60@3.[175,1411,193,1954]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–5. Habitus of Baptista spp.. 1. B. digitata, male; 2. B. digitata, female; 3. B. hoedli, male; 4. B. hoedli, female; 5. B. hoedli, apterous male. Scale 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4918939" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4918939/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">Fig 2</figureCitation>
).
</emphasis>
Similar to male in general structure and coloration, body length: 2.93; structure of head including antenna as in male, head about 1.47 times as wide as long, antennae about 0.66 times as long as body, lengths of antennal segments I–IV: 0.44, 0.28, 0.57, 0.63; pronotum as in male, width: 0.95, length: 0.55, about 1.73 times as wide as long; fore femur unmodified, fore tibia straight and without grasping comb, lengths of leg segments (femur, tibia and tarsi): fore leg: 0.90, 0.72 and 0.34, middle leg: 1.00, 0.90, and 0.39 (0.14+0.25), hind leg: 1.07, 1.19, and 0.48 (0.22+0.26); abdomen pleurally and ventrally without special modifications; connexiva broad, approximately rectangular, vertically raised throughout, converging posteriorly and touching caudally; gonocoxae and proctiger relatively small, proctiger with acute apex.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BDF36976D6896105FAFFB038255FB2E" blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1544]" box="[199,881,1231,1256]" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">
<emphasis id="B914EA856D6896105FAFFB038035FB2E" bold="true" box="[199,273,1231,1256]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="303" reason="1">Notes.</emphasis>
This species is recorded for the first time from 
<collectingCountry id="F37776076D6896105C4EFB038249FB2E" box="[806,877,1231,1256]" name="China" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">China</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C37A651C6D6896105FAFFB3880FEFA23" pageId="2" pageNumber="303" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BDF36976D6896105FAFFB3880FEFA23" blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1544]" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">
<emphasis id="B914EA856D6896105FAFFB388068FACB" bold="true" box="[199,332,1268,1293]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="303" reason="1">Discussion.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFF14B666D6896105E3BFB38832BFACB" author="Andersen, N. M." box="[339,527,1268,1293]" pageId="2" pageNumber="303" pagination="363 - 380" refId="ref7313" refString="Andersen, N. M. (1989) The Old World Microveliinae (Hemiptera: Veliidae). II. Three new species of Baptista Distant and a new genus from the Oriental region. Entomologica Scandinavica, 19, 363 - 380. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1163 / 187631289 x 00258" type="journal article" year="1989">Andersen (1989)</bibRefCitation>
gave an excellent description of 
<taxonomicName id="4C604D146D6896105CE9FB3982D3FACA" authorityName="Andersen" authorityYear="1989" box="[897,1015,1268,1292]" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Baptista" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="303" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="digitata">
<emphasis id="B914EA856D6896105CE9FB3982D3FACA" box="[897,1015,1268,1292]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="303">B. digitata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and illustrated the range of variation from the largest to the smallest male forms (Figs. 
<quantity id="4C989B726D6896105DB1FADB8219FAF6" box="[729,829,1303,1328]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.334" metricValueMax="5.842" metricValueMin="4.826" pageId="2" pageNumber="303" unit="in" value="21.0" valueMax="23.0" valueMin="19.0">19–23 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation id="EFF14B666D6896105C2FFADB82DAFAF6" author="Andersen, N. M." box="[839,1022,1303,1328]" pageId="2" pageNumber="303" pagination="363 - 380" refId="ref7313" refString="Andersen, N. M. (1989) The Old World Microveliinae (Hemiptera: Veliidae). II. Three new species of Baptista Distant and a new genus from the Oriental region. Entomologica Scandinavica, 19, 363 - 380. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1163 / 187631289 x 00258" type="journal article" year="1989">Andersen, 1989</bibRefCitation>
); the modifications of the male fore femur and abdominal segments VI–VII are much more pronounced in larger males than in smaller ones. The diagnostic features of our specimen match well with the original description of the largest form, although they differ slightly in regard to some structures: the fingerlike projection of segment VI is slightly shorter; the median keel on abdominal ventrites VI and VII is slightly wider; and the tooth of the basal part of the proctiger is shorter and nearly indistinguishable.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
